cluster_relations.rel_desc: Biased algorithms in hiring perpetuate or sustain discriminatory outcomes.
A lack of transparency in AI systems can cause or result in distrust in those systems.

args.canonical_rel_desc: Indicates that the subject is a causal factor that leads to the occurrence or persistence of the object outcome or state, potentially under specified conditions or with uncertainty qualifiers.
args.justification: All relations describe a causal effect where the subject (biased or incomplete data, AI systems under certain training conditions, biased algorithms, lack of transparency) leads to a harmful or negative outcome (discriminatory outcomes, discrimination, distrust). The qualifiers already encode conditionality and modality (e.g., 'can', 'if'), so a single canonical predicate 'causes' appropriately captures the underlying causal semantics across these instances.

Each relation instance expresses that one factor has a causal effect on another outcome (e.g., biased data leading to discriminatory outcomes, lack of transparency leading to distrust). Grouping them under the class 'causal_effect_relation' captures this shared semantic of directed causal influence without restricting it to a specific domain beyond causality.
All relations involve a directional causal link where one factor leads to or sustains another harmful outcome or state, fitting squarely into the broad semantic group of CAUSALITY.
